    {
      "name": "mchorse.mappet.api.scripts.user",
      "doc": "This section covers main Scripting API.\n\n <p>Here is an example script. If you put following code into world's\n <code>mappet/scripts/example.js</code> and execute command\n <code>/mp script eval @r example</code>, then you'll get teleported to\n (249, 56, -789) and you'll see the message in the chat.</p>\n\n <pre>{@code\n    function main(c)\n    {\n        // Teleport the subject entity to specific coordinates, and\n        // send a message to everyone on the server\n        c.getSubject().setPosition(249, 56, -789);\n\n        c.send(\"Teleported \" + c.getSubject().getName() + \" to (249, 56, -789)\");\n    }\n }</pre>"
    },
    {
      "name": "mchorse.mappet.api.scripts.user.items",
      "doc": "This section covers Items. Here you can find all interfaces which relate to the items."
    },
    {
      "name": "mchorse.mappet.api.scripts.user.logs"
    },
    {
      "name": "mchorse.mappet.api.scripts.user.mappet",
      "doc": "Welcome to Mappet's in-game scripting documentation!\n\n <p>Scripts are JavaScript (ES 5.1) programs that allow you to program game\n logic.</p>\n\n <p>Scripts are stored in world's <code>mappet/scripts/</code> folder.\n The filename without extension of the script is its ID. Depending on\n the configuration of the script, there might be an additional JSON file\n with extra non-code data.</p>\n\n <p>Here are global variable(s) that are provided by Mappet:</p>\n\n <ul>\n     <li><code>mappet</code>, it's a {@link mchorse.mappet.api.scripts.user.IScriptFactory}.\n     It allows you to create and query different Minecraft or Mappet data structures.</li>\n </ul>\n\n <p>There are currently two packages available in Mappet:</p>\n\n <ul>\n     <li><code>Scripting API</code> section covers functions that allow you to interact with\n     Minecraft's mechanics to some extent and with Mappet.</li>\n     <li><code>UI API</code> section covers functions that allow you to create custom user\n     intrfaces (UI) which can be used for plethora of things.</li>\n </ul>\n\n <p>Big thanks to TorayLife for scripting API suggestions.</p>"
    },
    {
      "name": "mchorse.mappet.api.scripts.user.nbt",
      "doc": "This section covers NBT. Here you can find all interfaces which relate to the NBT."
    },
    {
      "name": "mchorse.mappet.api.ui.components",
      "doc": "UI API is an Application Programming Inteface (API) which allows you\n to create custom graphical User Intefaces (UI). It could be used for\n plethora of things:\n\n <p>Custom dialogue system, disabling user input, diaries (discovering\n notes, logs, lore fragments, etc.), mini-games, unlocking doors,\n point-and-click games, player creation screen, custom administration\n tools, custom quest quest offers, and so on.</p>\n\n <p><b>All</b> UI components are based off {@link mchorse.mappet.api.ui.components.UIComponent},\n therefore they all have UIComponent's methods.</p>\n\n <p>Here is a really basic example that drops an item upon pressing\n a button:</p>\n\n <pre>{@code\n    function main(c)\n    {\n        var ui = mappet.createUI(c, \"handler\").background();\n        var button = ui.button(\"Give me a diamond!\").id(\"button\");\n\n        button.rxy(0.5, 0.5).wh(160, 20).anchor(0.5);\n        c.getSubject().openUI(ui);\n    }\n\n    function handler(c)\n    {\n        var s = c.getSubject();\n        var uiContext = s.getUIContext();\n\n        if (uiContext.getLast() === \"button\")\n        {\n            var pos = s.getPosition();\n\n            c.getWorld().dropItemStack(mappet.createItem(\"minecraft:diamond\"), pos.x, pos.y + 2, pos.z);\n        }\n    }\n }</pre>"
    },
